<h2>Solar Incentives in San Francisco</h2>
<p>San Francisco residents have access to multiple solar incentives that significantly reduce installation costs. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit on the total system cost, including equipment and installation, through 2032. California offers additional state-level incentives, including the California Solar Initiative and net energy metering through PG&E, which allows homeowners to sell excess electricity back to the grid at retail rates. PG&E also provides rebates and time-of-use rate plans that maximize savings for solar customers. San Francisco's Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing program allows homeowners to finance solar installations through their property taxes, making solar more accessible regardless of upfront costs. The city also offers expedited permitting processes for solar installations, reducing both time and administrative costs.</p>

<h2>Best Solar Companies in San Francisco</h2>
<p>When selecting a solar installer in San Francisco, prioritize companies with proper California Contractors State License Board (CSLB) licensing, specifically C-46 (Solar) classification. Look for installers with extensive experience in San Francisco's unique architectural challenges, including Victorian homes, steep roofs, and urban shading issues. Top-rated companies should offer comprehensive warranties covering equipment (typically 20-25 years for panels), workmanship (minimum 10 years), and performance guarantees. Verify that installers are certified by the North American Board of Certified Energy Practitioners (NABCEP) and have strong local references. Given San Francisco's fog and marine climate, choose companies experienced with microinverters or power optimizers to maximize production in partially shaded conditions. Reputable installers will provide detailed shade analysis, multiple financing options, and handle all permitting and PG&E interconnection paperwork.</p>

